    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 115, n. <citedRange>106</citedRange>, fig. 62</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.218</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>026200</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#beschi1970"/>, p. <citedRange>205</citedRange> (date of the base)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>140</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.72</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-64557"><name nymRef="#Καρνήδας">Καρνήδας</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-64425"><name nymRef="#Ἰσοκράτης" type="patronymic">Ἰσοκράτευς</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Karnèdas fils d'Isokratès.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Karnedas son of Isokrates.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Karnedas figlio di Isokrates.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Beschi dated the base in the 1st half of second century BC, but the lettering seems older (so also <bibl><ptr target="#fraser-matthews1987"/>,
                pp. <citedRange>239, 252</citedRange></bibl>, following J.M. Reynolds' opinion).</p>
	<p>The Thorns assumed that this base might come from the North Necropolis because the Italian archaeologists worked mainly in that sector before World War II.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
